Hypothesis Testing

Do two samples come from the same population?

library(pwr)
library(epitools)
library(DescTools)
library(bioanth)
library(nortest)
library(fBasics)
library(car)
library(effsize)

library(rstatix)
library(coin)

It is unlikely that we have been able to collect data from the whole population; therefore, it is likely that we want to examine if two samples/sub-samples come from the same population

  • Hypothesis testing: allows us to assign a probability to the possibility that two samples were drawn from the same population (or from populations with the same parameters)

  • Effect size: measure used to assess the magnitude of an effect

Hypothesis Testing

  • Null hypothesis (\( H_{0} \)): the two groups have the same distribution (i.e., there is no difference between them) (this is what is assumed to be true)

    • Compute the probability that we would get the observed results if there was no difference between the groups

    • If you find that there is no statistically significant difference, it is not that you accept there is no difference, but that you fail to reject that there is no difference

      • Avoid the conclusion that it now means there is nothing to explain - there may be valuable information still present, or the test was not strong enough to identify differences
      • Avoid thinking “there is no difference or relationship or effect”

  • Test statistic: the statistic that is computed and comapred to a particular standardized sampling distributed

Type I versus Type II error

  • Type I error (\( \alpha \)): reject the null hypothesis when the null hypothesis is actually true
    • An \( \alpha \) of 0.05 suggests that if you were to replicate your sampling 100 times, 5% of the time you would get a test statistic indicative of a significant result even if there isn't
[1] 0.0482

  - You cannot take a rejection of the null hypothesis as proof that the alternative hypothesis is true - you may have received an extreme statistic completely be chance
  • Type II error (\( \beta \)): failing to reject the null hypothesis when it is actually false
    • In general, we want less than a .2 probability that this would happen
    • Decreasing the \( \alpha \) level simply increases the \( \beta \)
    • Increases chance of Type II error: 1) Lower significance value 2) Larger standard deviation 3) Larger standard error
\( H_{0} \) True \( H_{0} \) False
Reject \( H_{0} \) False Positive (Type I error; \( \alpha \)) True Positive (Power; 1- \( \beta \))
Fail to reject \( H_{0} \) True Negative False Negative (Type II error; \( \beta \))

$\alpha$-level and Statistical Power

  • \( \alpha \): the significance level used to reject the null hypothesis

    • If the p-value is greater than \( \alpha \) than there is not enough evidence against the null hypothesis
    • If the p-value is lower than \( \alpha \) than there is enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis (statistically significant)

  • Statistical power (1- \( \beta \)): the probability of correctly rejecting the null hypothesis when it is false

    • Statistically powerful = 0.8
    • Ability of the test to detect a real effect

    • Affected by:

      1) Sample size

      2) Effect size

      3) $\alpha$

Increased sample size, effect size, or \( \alpha \) increases power

P-values

  • The probability that a specific statistic (e.g., mean) would be equal to or more extreme than its observed value

  • ASA statement on p-values:

    • P-values can indicate how incompatible the data are with a specified statistical model
    • P-values do not measure the probability that the studied hypothesis is true, or the probability that the data were produced by random chance alone
    • Scientific conclusions and business of policy decisions should not be based only on whether a p-value passes a specific threshold
    • Proper inference requires full reporting and transparency
    • A p-value, or statistical significance, does not measure the size of an effect or the importance of a result
    • By itself, a p-value does not provide a good measure of evidence regarding a model or hypothesis

  • p-values indicate how surprised we should be to see the data occurring by chance

  • p-values are calculated based on the assumption that the null hypothesis is true (p = 0.01 does not mean there is a 1% chance the null hypothesis is true)

Does significant mean strong?

No

  • Just because you have a significant result does not mean that you know the strength of the association nor that the difference is practically important
  • As the sample sizes increase, it is possible to reject the null hypothesis with smaller differences between the samples

Effect Size

  • Usually a standardized estimate of the magnitude of an effect
    • Standardized so that you can compare across samples and statistics
  • Impacted by:
    • Sample size
    • The \( \alpha \)-level
    • Statistical power

How can we test for significant differences?

Categorical Data

  • Proportions tests

  • Chi-square

  • Fisher's Exact

Parametric Continuous Data

  • t-test

Nonparametric Continuous Data and Ordinal Data

  • Mann-Whitney U

  • Wilcoxon signed-rank tests

Z Proportions test

  • For large enough samples, a normal distribution approximation of a binomial distribution may be used to compare proportions

\( Z \) = \( \frac{p_{1}-p_{2}}{\sqrt{\frac{\hat{p}(1-\hat{p}}{n_1}}+\frac{\hat{p}(1-\hat{p}}{n_2}} \)

\( p \) = \( \frac {f_{1}+f_{2}}{n_{1}+n_{2}} \)

  • The denominator is the standard error of the difference between two proportions - information about how variable the sample statistic (proportion) is between multiple samples

  • Test statistic, \( Z \), is compared to critical values from the normal distribution

If you want to use a power analysis to estimate what your sample sizes need to be, etc. either h, n1, n2, or sig.level needs to be left NULL. The function will estimate what that parameter needs to be to have a powerful test.

Chi-square Distribution

  • Based on the binomial distribution (dichotomous data - “success/failure”)

  • Chi-square test of proportions examines the probability that the null hypothesis is correct based on the Chi-squared distribution

    • The chi-square distribution is a special form of the gamma distribution with one parameter (\( k \) - the degrees of freedom or one less than the number of categories)
    • The chi-square distribution is only positive and is right-skewed due to being based on the sum of squared quantities
    • The chi-square statistic is calculated and then compared to the chi-square distribution to get the probability of results
    • As degrees of freedom increases, chi-square distribution becomes more approximately normal

Chi-square test

There are three versions:

  • Chi-square test for independence/association: tests the null hypothesis that the variables are independent of each other - there is no relationship between the variables
    • Expected proportions estimated from data
  • Chi-square test for equality of proportions/homogeneity: tests the null hypothesis that the distribution of some variable is the same in all samples
    • Expected proportions estimated from data

Uses contingency tables to calculate expected frequencies compared to the observed frequencies

\( Model_{ij} \) = \( \frac{RT_i x CT_j}{n} \)

#chisq.test(Data, p = (vector of your a prior known expected probabilities))
#If data is a matrix and no p argument is provided, it will calculate an independence/homogeneity tests
#If data is a single column or row and the argument p is provided, it will calculate a goodness-of-fit test
#If data is a single column or row and the argument p is not provided, it will calculate a goodness-of-fit test with the assumption that the probabilities should all be equal

Then, do the observed frequencies differ significantly from the expected frequencies

\( \chi^{2} \) = \( \sum_{r = 1}^{R} \sum_{c = 1}^{C} n_{x} \frac{(p_{rc}- \pi_{rc})^{2}}{\pi_{r}} \)

\( \pi \) - the population proportion; expected proportion \( p \) - the sample proportion; observed proportion

  • Chi-square test of goodness of fit: tests the hypothesis that the distribution of a variable within a population follows a specific pattern of proportions

    • Expected proportions known a priori

      $\chi{2}$ = $n \sum{j = 1}{J} \frac{(p{j}-\pi{j})2}{\pi{j}}$

      • Effect size for goodness-of-fit:

      $\frac {\chi{2}}{N(J-1)}$

  • Assumptions:

    • Independence
    • Expected frequencies should be greater than 5

  • Null hypothesis: there is no significant difference between the proportions or that their difference is 0

  • Alternative hypothesis: the proportions are different

Assumptions

1) Categorical data

2) Expected frequencies must be at least 5 for each cell

Possible effect sizes

  • Odds ratio: essentially estimates the odds of an event occurring (the probability of an event occurring divided by the probability of the event not occurring) - In a 2x2 contingency table this would be

    $\frac{\frac{cellA}{CellC}}\frac{CellB}{CellD}}$

  • The phi (\( \phi \)) statistic can be calculated to determine the strength of association between two variables that have more than two levels
    • Used for 2X2 contingency tables
    • Binary data

\( \phi \) = \( \frac {ad-bc}{\sqrt{(a+b)(c+d)(a+c)(b+d)}} \) for ordered data (provides negative values)

or

\( \phi \) = \( \sqrt{\frac{\chi^2}{n}} \) for unordered data (does not provide negative values)

  • Cramer's V is an extension of the phi statistic for more levels of categorical data and larger contingency tables

\( V \) = \( \sqrt{\frac{\chi^2}{n(min r-1,c-1)}} \)

Fisher's Exact Test

  • Similar to chi-square; however, it can be used with small/sparse datasets that do not meet the requirements of a chi-square test
  • Typically used for 2x2 contingency tables, but can be used for larger
fisher.test(Chi_2x2_Example[2:3])


    Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data

95 percent confidence interval:
 1.900060 6.518197

odds ratio 
  3.499758

Effect size is odds ratio:

Calculated in this example by the number of adults Unaffected divided by Affected

AOR<-145/29

Then the number of juveniles unaffected divided by affected

JOR <- 54/38

And then the ratio of adults divided by the ratio of juveniles

OR <- AOR/JOR

#Essentially adults would be 3.516 times more likely to be unaffected than juveniles

Fisher's tests on tables larger than 2x2 and with very large frequencies can be a lot for R (for any statistical program). If you have large tables (many rows and many columns) and large sample sizes, consider alternative tests (you may meet the assumptions of Chi-square at that point).

What is the t-distribution?

  • Similar to the normal distribution and when the sample size is large, they are effectively equal
    • Smaller sample sizes have larger tailed t-distributions, producing wider confidence intervals to accomodate greater uncertainty in estimating the population parameters
  • One parameter: degrees of freedom \( (n-1) \)
  • The probability that that the sample does not contain the population parameter (\( 1-\alpha \)) is generally split between the left and right sides (0.25 for each side)

T-test

  • Compare continuous data for one sample or between two samples
  • Difference of means between two distributions
  • Uses the t-distribution to calculate if two means are significantly different from each other

Student t-test versus Welch's t-test

  • If variances are equal -> Student's t-test

\( t \)=\( \frac {\overline{X_1}-\overline{X_2}}{\sqrt{\frac{(n_{1}-1)s_{1}^{2}+(n_{2}-1)s_{2}^{2}}{n_1 + n_2 - 2}}{\sqrt{\frac{1}{n_1}\frac{1}{n_2}}}} \)

The numerator is the difference between the means of both samples

The denominator is the pooled standard error

The standard error is essentially used to assess if the difference between means is greater than chance; if there is a large standard error than we would expect there to be larger variability in the sampling distribution of the means; if there is a small standard error than we would expect there to be less variability in the sampling distribution of the means

  • Three assumptions of independent T-test:
    • The samples are independent of each other
    • The sampling distribution is normally distributed/continuous - For dependent samples, this means the differences between the scores of each sample should be normally distributed
    • Sample variances in the samples are equal (though if sample sizes are equal, you are generally okay)

One-sample t-test: does the mean of your sample differ from a proposed mean?

Two samples: do the means of two samples significantly differ from each other? - Do you expect the two means to be the same or that there is no specific direction (greater or lesser)? - “two.sided” - Do you expect the first (x = ) sample to be greater than the second (y = ) sample? - alternative = “greater” - Do you expect the first (x = ) sample to be less than the second (y = ) sample - alternative = “less”

Ex:) Your Norse dataset is divided into Males and Females Your hypothesis is that the means of each sex are the same.

Are my data appropriate for Student's t-test?

Now to calculate if the power of your tests are satisfactory:

library(pwr)

ttt2 <- twotest$statistic[[1]]
ttdf2 <- twotest$parameter[[1]]
ttr2 <- sqrt(ttt2^2/(ttt2^2+ttdf2))
pwr.t2n.test(n1 = 55, n2 = 56, d = ttr2, sig.level = 0.05, alternative = "two.sided") #Good power


     t test power calculation 

             n1 = 55
             n2 = 56
              d = 0.646961
      sig.level = 0.05
          power = 0.9218752
    alternative = two.sided

gtt2 <- twotest$statistic[[1]]
gtdf2 <- twotest$parameter[[1]]
gtr2 <- sqrt(gtt2^2/(gtt2^2+gtdf2))
pwr.t2n.test(n1 = 55, n2 = 56, d = gtr2, sig.level = 0.05, alternative = "greater") #Good power

  • If variances are not equal -> Welch's t-test (default in R and often most recommended by statisticians; more conservative approach)

\( t \) = \( \frac {\overline{X_1}- \overline{X_2}}{\sqrt{\frac{s_1^2}{n_1}} + \frac{s_2^2}{n_2}} \)

  • Less powerful alternative, meaning there is a greater chance of making a Type II error
  • However, if no correction is necessary, the adjustment does not actually apply any correction

Hypotheses

  • H0: There is no significant difference between the means of each group.

  • H1: There is a significant difference between the means of each group.

Assumptions

1) Two samples

2) Parametric continuous data (some skewness is okay if there are no outliers)

3) The samples are independent of each other

4) For Student's t-test, the samples need to have the same variance

Possible effect sizes

  • Cohen's d: the difference between the mean of the data and \( \mu \) divided by the data's standard deviation

    • Negative indicates the mean is less than \( \mu \)
    • Positive indicates the mean is more than \( \mu \)
Small Medium Large
0.2 - 0.5 0.5 - 0.8 > 0.8 
library(effsize)

cohen.d(d = Norse$MAB, f = Norse$Sex)

     lower      upper 
-1.6877664 -0.8587291

Independent versus Dependent t-test

  • Independent means: when there are two experimental conditions and different participants were assigned to each condition

    • Assumptions: - Independent from each other - Randomly selected - Normal distribution

  • Dependent means (paired samples/repeated measures): when there are two experimental conditions and the same participants took part in both conditions of the experiment

\( t \) = \( \frac {\overline{D}- \mu_D}{\frac{s_{D}}{\sqrt(N)}} \)

FHD <- read.csv("FHD.csv")

#Result <- t.test(scores of group 1, scores of group 2, data, paired = TRUE/FALSE, alternative = "two.sided","less","greater", na.action = na.exclude)

#alternative indicates what variation you want for the t-test; default is two.sided; one-sided t-tests included "less" where you predict that the difference between means will be less than zero and "greater" where you predict that the difference between means will be greater than zero
#na.action indicates what you want done if you have missing data; na.exclude indicates you want all cases that have missing data to be excluded

Multiple Comparisons

  • Bonferroni: divides the alpha value by the number of tests being done
    • Criticized for being overly conservative and resulting in a loss of power
    • Increased rated of Type II error (rejecting an effect when it actually does exist)

\( \alpha_{new} \) = \( \frac {\alpha}{n} \)

\( p_{crit} \) = \( \frac {\alpha}{n} \)

  • Holm's: compute the p-values for all pairs, then order them from smallest to largest -> each of the ranked p-values are now indexed with 1 being the largest, the next largest is 2, the next largest is 3, and so on
    • You then divide the paired tests p-value by its rank; this decreases the conservative nature of the correction as you get towards higher p-values

\( p_{crit} \) = \( \frac {\alpha}{j} \)

  • Hochberg's: does not focus on Type I error rate but rather on the false discovery rate - rather than trying to avoid Type I errors altogether, this estimates how many errors have been made
    • Aims to keep the FDR controlled more than the Type I error rate, making it less strict
    • p-values are calculated then indexed like Holm's method except in reverse, so here the smallest is 1 and the next smallest is 2 and so on

\( p_{crit} \) = \( (\frac {j}{k})\alpha \)

p.adjust(c(.033, .962, .244, .715, .029, .670, .515, .000), method = "bonferroni")

[1] 0.264 1.000 1.000 1.000 0.232 1.000 1.000 0.000

p.adjust(c(.033, .962, .244, .715, .029, .670, .515, .000), method = "holm")

[1] 0.203 1.000 1.000 1.000 0.203 1.000 1.000 0.000

p.adjust(c(.033, .962, .244, .715, .029, .670, .515, .000), method = "hochberg")

[1] 0.198 0.962 0.962 0.962 0.198 0.962 0.962 0.000

Mann-Whitney Test/Wilcoxon rank-sum test

  • Non-parametric alternative to t-test

    • Useful for non-normally distributed continuous data or ordinal data

  • Assesses if the rank values of one sample tend to be larger than the rank values of the other sample (null hypothesis is that there is no difference in the concentration of ranks between groups - one group does not show significantly more high or low ranks than the other group)

    • Similar to comparing the medians of two samples

  • Data is ranked from smallest to largest and assigned ranks

W = \( \sum R_1 - \frac{n_1(n_1 +1)}{2} \)

Wilcoxon signed-rank test

  • Essentially the non-parametric alternative to dependent samples t-test
  • Differences between scores are ranked with their signs attached (positive or negative)
    • Differences of 0 are not included

Effect size for the Wilcoxon ranked-sign test:

\( r \) = \( \frac {z}{\sqrt(n)} \)

(ResultFHD <- wilcox.test(FHD$LFHD, FHD$RFHD, paired = TRUE))
